From 429e257de18f8a5c8e69a4ad7674f87f09d5c837 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Salman Wahib <sxlmnwb.dev@gmail.com>
Date: Sat, 23 May 2026 16:24:10 +0700
Subject: [PATCH] mm/lru_marie: add AVX-512F+BW+BMI2 optimised PTE scanner for
 AMD Zen 5

Introduce mm/lru_marie_simd_x86_avx512_zen5.S, a Zen 5-specific SIMD
kernel for the Marie LRU PTE young-bit scanner, and wire it into the
boot-time dispatch in mm/lru_marie_simd_x86.c.

The upstream avx512f kernel targets the AVX-512F Foundation subset for
broad compatibility (Xeon Phi, early Skylake-SP). AMD Zen 5 exposes
AVX-512BW and BMI2 in addition to AVX-512F, enabling three further
optimisations that are unsafe or unavailable on the generic path:

1. SHLXQ (BMI2) replaces push/pop-around-shlq
   The upstream variable shift requires the count in CL, forcing
   push/pop of RCX (inner loop counter) on every inner iteration:
   2 extra uops x 64 inner iterations = 128 extraneous uops per call.
   SHLXQ shifts from any GPR without touching flags or CL, eliminating
   the push/pop pair entirely.

2. 2x inner-loop unroll (16 PTEs per iteration, up from 8)
   Zen 5 has two AVX-512 execution ports (p0/p1). Unrolling by 2 lets
   the two VPTESTMQ ops dual-issue in a single cycle. Loop overhead
   (dec+jnz) is halved. Inner loop drops from 8 to 4 iterations per
   outer pass.

3. vmovdqa64 replaces vmovdqu64
   The kernel page-table allocator guarantees 4096-byte alignment for
   PTE tables; 4096 is a multiple of 64, so all 512-bit ZMM loads are
   naturally aligned. vmovdqa64 avoids the alignment micro-op that
   vmovdqu64 inserts on Zen 5 L1D.

4. KMOVB (AVX-512BW) replaces KMOVW
   VPTESTMQ on an 8-lane ZMM produces exactly 8 result bits in
   k1[7:0]. KMOVB is semantically exact (8-bit opmask -> GPR,
   zero-extended to 64) and avoids an implicit dependency on the
   upper opmask bits that KMOVW carries.

5. Software prefetch (PREFETCHT0 256 bytes ahead)
   Issued at the top of each inner iteration to hide L1D fill latency
   for the next ZMM pair. Zen 5's hardware prefetcher handles
   sequential patterns well but benefits from the explicit hint at
   4 KB PTE table boundaries.

The new kernel is selected only when all three feature bits are
confirmed at boot (AVX512F + AVX512BW + BMI2); the existing
avx512f kernel remains the fallback for CPUs that lack BMI2 or
AVX-512BW.

A new read-only sysfs attribute, /sys/kernel/mm/lru_marie/simd_alg,
is added to report the boot-selected SIMD kernel name at runtime
("avx512f_zen5", "avx512f", "avx2", or "sse2").

Verified on:
  CPU:        AMD Ryzen AI 9 HX 370 (Zen 5, Strix Point)
  Kernel:     linux-7.0.y
  lru_marie:  0001-linux7.0-lru_marie-0.1.5.patch
  dmesg:      "SIMD PTE scan: AVX-512F+BW+BMI2 Zen5 (16 PTEs/iter)"
  sysfs:      /sys/kernel/mm/lru_marie/simd_alg = avx512f_zen5

Cc: Masahito S <firelzrd@gmail.com>
Signed-off-by: Salman Wahib <sxlmnwb.dev@gmail.com>
---
 include/linux/lru_marie_simd.h      |   9 +
 mm/Makefile                         |   1 +
 mm/lru_marie.c                      |   9 +
 mm/lru_marie_simd_x86.c             |  28 ++-
 mm/lru_marie_simd_x86_avx512_zen5.S | 345 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
 5 files changed, 388 insertions(+), 4 deletions(-)
 create mode 100644 mm/lru_marie_simd_x86_avx512_zen5.S

